accessrestrict.head: Access to Collection
accessrestrict.p: Apart from the materials in 2014-075, the materials are open for research use. Researchers must get permission from University Archivist to access materials in 2014-075. Audio-visual materials are not available in original format, and must be reformatted to a digital use copy.

userestrict.head: Publication Rights
userestrict.p: All requests to reproduce, publish, quote from, or otherwise use collection materials must be submitted in writing to the Head of Special Collections and University Archives, Stanford University Libraries, Stanford, California 94305-6064. Consent is given on behalf of Special Collections as the owner of the physical items and is not intended to include or imply permission from the copyright owner. Such permission must be obtained from the copyright owner, heir(s) or assigns. See: http://library.stanford.edu/spc/using-collections/permission-publish.
Restrictions also apply to digital representations of the original materials. Use of digital files is restricted to research and educational purposes.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Over the several decades that the human sexuality course was taught, some of the slides used in the class changed over time. Typically, I used 50 slides per lecture (25 slides each in two projectors).

The slides shown here are usually more than 50 for each lecture. This is because I have included here all of the slides I used over the years including a few that I kept in reserve which I never used. I have done this to provide a broader overview of the material covered in the course during its lifetime. This should also provide potential users of these slides a wider choice to choose from.

These slides were digitized in two sets and are contained in two Sections: Section #1 has 13 lectures; Section #2 has 12 lectures. Each lecture is in a separate file identified alphabetically. The files in Section #1 go from FILE A (for Anatomy) to FILE L (for Coitus). Only File O, The Study of Sexuality, does not follow the lecture sequence. It should be the first lecture but now appears after File N, Marriage and Parenthood. (The result of confusion between the number zero and the letter O during the digitization process).

The slides in each Section are numbered sequentially. In Section #1, they go from 1 to 839. In Section #2, from 1 to 1231. (Only the numbering sequence for File O is off for the reason given above). The relevant number is what appears at the beginning after the zeros. (In the original slides, each lecture was numbered separately. Thus File A it went from A1 to A 55. File B went B1 to B 60).

After this process of ordering the HB 10 lecture slides, I discovered another set of slides which I had used in a course that I taught at Albany Medical School. I have added these slides to the lecture topics they belong to and labeled them as Addendum, rather than Integrating these slides into the HB 10 sequence which would have required renumbering them The slides listed here are only those that required comments or explanations. Hence, there may be gaps in their sequence. For instance, in FILE A, slides 1-2 are followed by slide 7. These are mostly for identification rather than instructional purposes.

These lectures were never fully written out. There are brief notes written on the sides of the original slides but only some of these are reproduced here. My fragmentary lecture notes are also appended to this material. They may not be readily intelligible, (including to myself at this point). However, they may be useful in giving a general sense of my thinking in composing these lectures. The best source for complement these slides is my textbook, “Fundamentals of Human Sexuality”, Fifth Edition. Harcourt Brace, 1989.
